text: Climate change does not just mean that "the world gets warmer". It means that summers get hotter while winters get colder. Or that summers get colder while winters get hotter. Or that both stay at the exact same temperature. It's a flexible concept really. Covers a lot of ground.

It's insane that cardiology is the branch of medicine with simultaneously some of the worst drugs of all time (statins, Warfarin, almost all various diuretics, etc.) and some of the best drugs that actually work (Losartan, ACE inhibitors, Calcium blockers, beta blockers, aspirin)

It's like here is the best substance of all time that will prevent cancer and is anti-estrogenic and helps brain function and virility. Oh and here is something that will give you dementia and actually makes you die sooner and has no benefits whatsoever. Make sure to take both

A lot is written on nature's absence from civilization, but few is said on its perpetual proximity. A friend mentioned finding bobcat tracks far outside their range. I've heard someone saw hare footprints in the snow at the city square here, far from any conceivable "wild nature"

I've seen hedgehogs in the ghetto part of town here against nowhere close to a park or trees or anything where one could conceive them to live in. Wild animals just appear in cities at night. One almost feels it plausible to meet a bear or a wolf on a city backstreets nightwalk

The concept of "Funky Pops" as some cultural arch-villain has festered for too long on. A dozen or so redditors got a bit carried away with their infantile hobby and now we (I!) have to hear about it for a decade because people pretend like it's some relevant deep social malaise.

In an ideal world, every man and woman will have an Auguste Rodin sculpture (scaled down dimensionally) on top of their desk, to contemplate between reading PDFs. Maybe me and a girl can get a miniature "Le Baiser". We will inspect it like a CS:GO knife together. Or perform it.
